Featurization and Model Tuning Project¶

Context:¶

Concrete is the most important material in civil engineering. The concrete compressive strength is a highly nonlinear function of age and ingredients. These ingredients include cement, blast furnace slag, fly ash, water, superplasticizer, coarse aggregate, and fine aggregate.

Objective:¶

Modeling of strength of high performance concrete using Machine Learning

1. Deliverable -1 (Exploratory data quality report reflecting the following) (20 marks)¶

a. Univariate analysis (5 marks)¶

Description of all the variables in the dataset ¶

Note : As we do not have the domain knowledge, hence done some research on this topic and tried to understand the concepts and then written as per my knowledge.

-------All the ingredients are measured in kg in m3 mixture and strength is measured in MPa-------

-> cement :¶

Cement is actually an ingredient of concrete.It is a water-based binder used to bind other building materials together. It is used in the production of mortar(paste) and concrete during the construction process.

-> slag :¶

Slag is often used in concrete in combination with cement, it is also used in steel making process but mostly used in construction.

-> ash :¶

Ash acts like a cement and a right receipe of concrete and it improves the strength of concrete. It is also replace of cement.

-> water :¶

Water is the key ingredient, which when mixed with cement, forms a paste that binds the aggregate together. The water causes the hardening of concrete through a process called hydration. The role of water is important because the water to cement ratio is the most critical factor in the production of "perfect" concrete.

-> superplasticizer :¶

It is also known as high range water reducers, are additives used in making high strength concrete. They are the chemical compounds that enables the production of concrete with approx 15% less water content. In other words it allows reduction in water content.

-> coarse aggregate :¶

Generally coarse aggregate is crushed stones blended with finer aggregates (such as sand) to fill in the spaces left between the large pieces and to lock the larger pieces together. This reduces the amount of cement paste required and decreases the amount of shrinkage that could occur.

-> fine aggregate :¶

As mentioned in the previous variable 'fine aggregates' includes natural sand, crushed stones, gravel used in construction. Aggregates plays in the properties of both fresh and hardened concrete. The proportions between coarse and fine aggregates will change based on the unique characteristics of each aggregate.

-> age :¶

This variable represents the age of the concrete, is the time elapsed since it was poured in place and left to set. We can say that concrete strength increases over time

-> strength :¶

Last but not the least. It is our dependent/output variable which we want to predict under a given mixture of all above independent variables or we can say 'Ingredients'. It defines the strength of the concrete measured in MPa, it lets inspectors know how much pressure can be applied to the concrete before it cracks or fails.

Definition of Concrete strength in MPa.¶

A megapascal (MPa) is a measure of the compressive strength of concrete. It lets inspectors know how much pressure can be applied to the concrete before it cracks or fails. One MPa is equal to one million pascals (Pa); as a pascal is one newton of force per square meter, a megapascal is one million newtons per square meter. The higher the MPa of concrete, the stronger the material will be, and the less likely it is to fail.

Outliers Detection

  • First of all What are Outliers : Outliers are the datapoints in the dataset that are distant from all other observations. Data points that lies outside the distribution of the dataset. Outliers are also called as anomalies

  • Outliers causes significant impact for our statistical analysis, for mean and standard deviation

In [13]:
for col_name in df.columns[:-1]:
    q1 = df[col_name].quantile(0.25)
    q3 = df[col_name].quantile(0.75)
    iqr = q3 - q1
    
    low = q1-1.5*iqr
    high = q3+1.5*iqr

    # Showing the outliers in every column
    print('Number of outliers in',col_name,'is :', df[(df[col_name] < low) | (df[col_name] > high)][col_name].count())

  • Here i have used IQR. IQR is a technique that one can use to detect and remove outliers. The formula for IQR is very simple. IQR = Q3-Q1. Where Q3 is 75th percentile and Q1 is 25th percentile. Once we have IQR we can find upper and lower limit by removing this formula, low = q1-1.5iqr high = q3+1.5iqr
  • Anything less than a lower limit or above the upper limit is considered outlier.
  • we have many techniques to detect the outliers like zscore, Percentile, log transformation method.
  • We can see that slag, water, superplastic and age contain outliers and we will impute them with thier respective column median value
In [15]:
for col_name in df.columns[:-1]:
    q1 = df[col_name].quantile(0.25)
    q3 = df[col_name].quantile(0.75)
    iqr = q3 - q1
    
    low = q1-1.5*iqr
    high = q3+1.5*iqr

    # replacing the outliers with median of respective column
    df.loc[(df[col_name] < low) | (df[col_name] > high), col_name] = df[col_name].median()
    
    # Checking after treating the outliers
    print('Number of outliers in',col_name,'is :', df[(df[col_name] < low) | (df[col_name] > high)][col_name].count())

Number of outliers in cement is : 0
Number of outliers in slag is : 0
Number of outliers in ash is : 0
Number of outliers in water is : 0
Number of outliers in superplastic is : 0
Number of outliers in coarseagg is : 0
Number of outliers in fineagg is : 0
Number of outliers in age is : 0
  • We saw that slag, water, superplastic had outliers and we imputed them with thier respective column median value
  • Now we can see that there are zero outliers in the dataset

b. Decide on complexity of the model, should it be simple linear model in terms of parameters or would a quadratic or higher degree help (5 marks)¶

  • In machine learning, model complexity often refers to the number of features or terms included in a given predictive model, as well as whether the chosen model is linear, nonlinear, and so on.

  • There are some linear models/methods which can control model complexity as well as helps to prevent over fitting

  • As there are not too many variables in the dataset, we can say model will not suffer much with complexity. If there are too many variables, leads to overfitting. Some of them are able to help with feature and model selection as well.

  • We have to take care of both over fitting and under fitting when building the predictive modelling. Should balance between both bias and variance

  • High bias leads to underfit and high variance leads to overfit. In both cases, the model will not make very accurate predictions on new data

  • The two most popular regularization methods in the linear regression are ridge regression and lasso. Both methods involve adding a tuning parameter (lambda) to the model, which is designed to impose a penalty on each term's coefficient based on its size, or effect on the model. They penalize large magnitude coefficients when it is set to a high number, coefficients are suppressed significantly, so we can choose the variables according to thier coefficients.

  • There are various regression models in supervised learning technique and will try to implement those and observe the accuracies.

from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

x = df.iloc[:,:-1] # Features 
y = df.iloc[:,-1] # Target 
x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=2) 
sc = StandardScaler() 
x_train = sc.fit_transform(x_train) 
x_test = sc.transform(x_test)

  • We will start with Linear Regression since this is the go-to algorithm for any regression problem. The algorithm tries to form a linear relationship between the input features and the target variable i.e. it fits a straight line

  • Magnitude od the Coefficients of Linear Regression can be controlled by other regularisationn terms by using lasso and ridge regression.

  • Both these variations help in reducing the model complexity and therefore reducing the chances of overfitting on the data.

from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score

y_pred_lr = lr_model.predict(x_test)
y_pred_lasso = lasso_model.predict(x_test)
y_pred_ridge = ridge_model.predict(x_test)

print("Model\t\t\t RMSE \t\t R2") 
print("""LinearRegression \t {:.2f} \t\t{:.2f}""".format(  np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_lr)), 
                                                         r2_score(y_test, y_pred_lr)))

Fine tuning machine learning predictive model is a crucial step to improve accuracy of the forecasted results.We will use GridSearchCV to find out the best hyperparameters. Hyperparameters are parameters of the models that can be input as arguments to the models.

Parameter Tuning Using GridDSearch

Using grid search to obtain combination of hyperparameter values of a model that can give us better accuracy. Grid Search evaluates all possible combinations of the parameter values.

c. Model performance range at 95% confidence level (10 marks)¶

In [49]:
# Function to perform cross validation and to display the cross validation mean accuracies across several run

from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score  

scores =[]
def model(algo, x, y):  # defining a function
    cross_val = cross_val_score(algo,x,y,cv=20) # 20 splits
    print ('************************')
    scores.append(cross_val)
    print ("cv-mean :",cross_val.mean())  # printing the average of all the 20 scores
    print ("cv-std  :",cross_val.std())   # printing the standard deviation to check the spread among all the scores
In [50]:
print('Decision Tree cv score')
model(dt_model,x, y)

print('\n')

print('Random Forest CV score')
model(rf_model,x, y)

In [51]:
# plot scores
plt.hist(scores[1])
plt.show()
# confidence intervals
alpha = 95       # for 95% confidence level
lower =  scores[1].mean()-(scores[1].std()*2) # minus two standard deviation
upper = scores[1].mean()+(scores[1].std()*2)  # plus two standard deviation
print('{}% confidence interval {:.1f}% and {:.1f}%'.format(alpha,lower*100,upper*100))

95% confidence interval 74.9% and 97.0%
  • The cross validation mean score of Random forest is better than simple decision tree model and we can give the range estimate of performance of the model.
  • We can say that our model would perform in the range between 83% and 97% with 95% of the confidence interval

Conclusion¶

We have analysed the Compressive Strength Data and used Machine Learning to Predict the Compressive Strength of Concrete. We have used Linear Regression and its variations, Decision Trees and Random Forests to make predictions and compared their performance. Random Forest Regressor has the lowest RMSE and is a good choice for this problem. Also, we further improved the performance of the algorithm by tuning the hyperparameters by performing a grid search so that our model not become overfit

By above dataframe we can see that Random Forest using cross validation gives us good mean accuracy so that we can give a range estimate in terms of our model performance in the real world As we mentioned in the earlier ensemble of the models performs better with this kind of dataset
